German <b>Butterweck</b>: metonymic occupational name for a baker of fine (white) breads etc., from Middle High German <i>buter</i> ‘butter’ + <i>wecke</i> ‘roll, biscuit’."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttrick","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place called Butterwick (see   Butterwick  ). Compare   Butrick  .","History: William Buttrick came from Kingston-upon-Thames, Surrey, England, to Concord, MA, in 1640."]},{"name":"Butterick","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Butterwick  . Compare   Buttrick  ."]}]},{"name":"Lucia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the old Roman given name <i>Lucius</i>, which is probably a derivative of Latin <i>lux</i> ‘light’. The girl's name is common in Italy and elsewhere, and is found as a learned, Latinate doublet of   Lucy   in England.  St Lucia  of Syracuse, who was martyred in  304 , was a very popular saint in the Middle Ages; she is often represented in medieval art as blinded and with her eyes on a platter, but the tradition that she had her eyes put out is probably based on nothing more than the association between light and eyes."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lucia Batterwick was born about 1242, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Reginald Butterwick and Agnes. She had at least 3 sons with John Barton. She died about 1324, at the age of 84."},"et":{"ABT. 1242–abt 1324":"umbes 1242–umbes 1324","1242–1324":"1242–1324","1240–1324":"1240–1324","1266–1336":"1266–1336","1270–1358":"1270–1358","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","abt 1324":"umbes 1324","1358":"1358","1336":"1336","1324":"1324","ABT. 1242":"umbes 1242","1266":"1266","abt 1270":"umbes 1270","1242":"1242","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","abt 1266":"umbes 1266","Fryton, Yorkshire, England":"Fryton, Yorkshire, England","York Co., England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT. 1242–abt 1324":"noin 1242–noin 1324",